      {
        "id": 2745838,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-11-03T18:58:44.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"155848\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>I had to google otiose (great word by the way), Around 15 years ago friend of mine turned up with a bottle of the 1966 which was drinking very well and shared a lot of similar characteristics of your note.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>That makes sense for the vintage. I think anywhere outside of Northern Europe, '65 Clos des Papes would likely be on its last legs, but in general the aging potential of unreconstructed Ch\u00e2teauneuf was considerable. Since it was not really a commodity wine, it is largely available in the form of odd bottles rather than whole cases, but I am buying more and more, from the '40s through the '80s, and I am seldom disappointed. Generally, what I buy from cellars in northern France is better than the old wines I have tasted in cellars in Ch\u00e2teauneuf, where cellars are mostly quite warm (with some exceptions). Previously, 1972 was the oldest Clos des Papes I have drunk, but I cannot wait to go further back in time. Speaking simply as a consumer, I would love to see the region reconnect with its roots in the form of wines like these.</p>",
        "post_number": 3,
        "post_type": 1,
